<DOC><DOCNO> AP891001-0062 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 1922EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0696 10-01 0571</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,0585</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Rain In Southeast Threatens Flooding</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after lead to UPDATE with tornado hitting Georgia,killing two.</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Up to 7 inches of rain fell Sunday over parts of the Southeast,causing lowland flooding and prompting widespread flash floodwatches, and snow fell in parts of Montana.   In the southern Georgia town of Moultrie, a tornado killed awoman and an infant, injured a dozen more people and destroyed achurch in a 10-mile rampage Sunday afternoon.   Rising water forced evacuation of more than 50 people from oneNorth Carolina mobile home park.   Flash flood watches were posted into early Monday morning oversoutheastern West Virginia, western Virginia, western NorthCarolina, western South Carolina and northern Georgia.   Two inches of rain or more fell Saturday and Sunday over westernsections of the Carolinas and northern Georgia, as well as acrossthe western Florida Panhandle.   Athens, Ga., got 7.64 inches of rain during the 24 hours up tonoon EDT.   Record flooding was predicted on the Oconee River at Penfield,Ga. Flood stage is 11 feet and the river reached 19.7 feet Sunday,with a crest of about 24 feet forecast Monday, the National WeatherService said.   Authorities in Gaston County, N.C., evacuated 53 residents of 30mobile homes in a low-lying park, said Tom Riley, Gaston Countycommunications coordinator. Lincoln County authorities helpedevacuate residents of a house threatened by a nearby overflowingcreek, said Bill Hoover, a dispatcher with the Lincoln CountySheriff's Department.   ``We have just urged caution. It's probably as bad as it's goingto get,'' said a dispatcher in Polk County, N.C., where three lowbridges were covered by water.   Rain began falling in western North Carolina late Thursday ``andit's been raining since,'' said Hank Moore of the weather servicein Asheville. He said 2 to 7 inches had fallen in some areas.   ``We're saturated not only from (hurricane) Hugo, but fromrainfall earlier in the month,'' Moore said.   A few back roads in south-central Tennessee were closed bywater, the weather service said.   Creeks in Pulaski County, Va., were nearly full and there wasminor flooding along Back Creek, the weather service said, but rainstopped during the morning and no serious flooding was expectedthere.   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included2.41 inches at Ozark, Ala.; 2.0 at Athens, Ga.; 1.88 at Greer,S.C.; 1.46 at Macon, Ga.; 1.43 at Huntsville, Ala.; 1.42 atHickory, N.C.; 1.38 at Dothan, Ala.; 1.30 at Atlanta; 1.24 atMarietta, Ga.; 1.23 at Panama City, Fla.; 1.15 at Anniston, Ala.;and 1.02 at Charlotte, N.C.   Showers and thunderstorms also extended northward into southernPennsylvania, central Ohio, Kentucky and southern Illinois.   Elsewhere, showers reached from South Dakota across northernWyoming into south-central Montana, with snow at higher elevationsof Montana near Lewiston.   A cold front in the Rockies kicked up wind gusting to 71 mph atBoulder, Colo.   Livestock advisories were posted over northern Wyoming becauseof a combination of cold, gusty wind and rain changing to snow,with accumulations of up to 5 inches predicted in the Big HornMountains of north-central Wyoming.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 95 at Phoenix. Sunday's low for theLower 48 states was 24 at Gunnison, Colo., and Union Village, Vt.</TEXT></DOC>